Reference-contexts: Acquisition and non-lexical cues..Among language-acquisition researchers, the focus of research has been constraints on the forms of words in particular languages. For example, the predominant stress pattern for bisyllabic words in English is strong-weak (e.g., mommy); weak-strong words (e.g., allow) are substantially rarer <ref> (Cutler & Carter, 1987) </ref>. There is now evidence that English-learning 9-month-olds know this (Jusczyk, Cutler, & Redanz, 1993a) and show a greater tendency to segment out strong-weak words than weak-strong words (Jusczyk, Newsome, & Houston, 1995).
