Reference-contexts: Brent, Lexical acquisition and lexical access 3 On-line Segmentation using a Lexicon..There has also been work on segmentation by researchers interested in on-line lexical access during continuous speech recognition. This work includes two well-known connectionist models: TRACE (McClelland & Elman, 1986) and Shortlist <ref> (Norris, 1994) </ref>. In these models, segmentation of utterances results from the recognition of familiar words. I refer to this as the lexical approach to segmentation. TRACE and Shortlist are aimed at explaining a range of behavioral data, including data about the time course of lexical activation during on-line speech recognition. <p> For example, it does not predict how people determine the most likely completion of the current partial word. Two models that do make predictions the time course of lexical activation during on-line segmentation are TRACE (McClelland & Elman, 1986) and Shortlist <ref> (Norris, 1994) </ref>. In one form or another, each of these models maintains an explicit "activation level" for individual words, including potential completions of currently incoming partial words.
